<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[192,1440,610,795]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,355,610,634]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Description</emphasis>
. Length of male 
<quantity box="[555,626,611,634]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" unit="mm" value="7.0">7 mm</quantity>
. One species was described by Dietrich, in 
<bibRefCitation author="Dietrich, C. H. &amp; F. E. Vega" box="[1133,1435,610,635]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" pagination="263 - 270" refId="ref5517" refString="Dietrich, C. H., and F. E. Vega. 1995. Leafhoppers (Homoptera: Cicadellidae) from Dominican Amber. Annals of the Entomological Society of America 88 (3): 263 - 270." type="journal article" year="1995">Dietrich and Vega (1995)</bibRefCitation>
, for an amber-preserved specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[663,841,642,666]" name="Dominican Republic" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">the Dominican</collectingCountry>
Republic. This description is adequate to describe this genus and the species. The main characters that differ from other genera is the anterior margin of the head is not sharply foliaceous as in present day New World species, but not bluntly rounded as in the Old World genus 
<taxonomicName box="[395,478,739,762]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Krisna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[395,478,739,762]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Krisna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Also the male seventh sternum is greatly expanded and the subgenital plates are very long which is not found in present day species. Only the one species is known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[192,1440,834,890]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,340,834,858]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Etymology</emphasis>
. The genus name is formed from the Greek stem archi- meaning first or ancient in combination with the name krisna. The gender is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
